## Overview

North NJ Services is a local business directory serving Passaic, Bergen, Morris, and Sussex counties in Northern New Jersey. The design language is **Trusted Neighbor** — authoritative without being corporate, warm without being cute. Think of a well-maintained town bulletin board, not a cold data aggregator.

The primary navy (`#0f3460`) communicates reliability and depth, while the coral accent (`#e94560`) adds urgency and warmth — drawing the eye to CTAs, categories, and ratings. The warm off-white canvas (`#f8f7f4`) avoids the clinical feel of pure white and creates an approachable surface that works for both homeowners scrolling on their couch and contractors checking competitors on a job site.

Typography is Inter throughout — chosen for its excellent readability at small sizes (critical for phone numbers and addresses) and its professional feel without being stuffy. Headings use weight 600-700, body stays at 400, and category labels use small-caps tracking for scannability.

Cards are the primary unit. Both category cards and business listing cards use generous padding, soft shadows, and gentle border-radius to feel substantial and readable. The left-border accent on business cards (`3px solid navy`) creates a visual rhythm when scanning a list, while the count badges and star ratings give quick visual anchors for decision-making.

**Key Characteristics:**
- Mobile-first directory — every card, listing, and CTA must work beautifully at 375px
- Warm canvas (`#f8f7f4`) instead of pure white — feels like paper, not pixels
- Navy + coral two-tone with no gradient on cards (gradients reserved for hero and CTA bands only)
- Inter typeface throughout — clear, professional, readable at all sizes
- Left-border accent on business cards creates visual rhythm in listing grids
- Category emoji icons for instant recognition — functional, not decorative
- Sticky nav for quick category switching while browsing
- Star ratings in gold (`#f59e0b`) for trust signaling
- Coming-soon badges in muted soft gray — honest about what's available vs. aspirational

## Colors

### Brand & Accent
- **Primary Navy** (`{colors.primary}` — `#0f3460`): The authoritative backbone. Used for headings, nav background, card borders, and the section title underline. It reads as dependable and local — not cold corporate navy, but deep trustworthy blue.
- **Accent Coral** (`{colors.accent}` — `#e94560`): The action color. CTAs, count badges, category labels, and hover states. It's warm, urgent, and unmistakably clickable against the navy and white palette.
- **Accent Hover** (`{colors.accent-hover}` — `#d63851`): Slightly deeper coral for button hover states.

### Surface
- **Canvas Warm** (`{colors.canvas-warm}` — `#f8f7f4`): The default page background. Warmer than pure white — has a subtle yellow undertone that reads as approachable paper rather than screen glare. Used for the `<body>` and section backgrounds.
- **Canvas** (`{colors.canvas}` — `#ffffff`): Pure white for card surfaces and modal overlays. Cards sit slightly elevated on the warm canvas.
- **Canvas Soft** (`{colors.canvas-soft}` — `#f4f3f0`): Slightly deeper warm gray for alternate section backgrounds and ad banner fills.
- **Surface Dark** (`{colors.surface-dark}` — `#1a1a2e`): The deep navy-navy gradient used for the header, footer, and CTA sections. Not black — has enough blue to feel cohesive with the primary navy.

### Text
- **Ink** (`{colors.ink}` — `#1a1a2e`): Primary heading color. Deep and readable on all light surfaces.
- **Body** (`{colors.body}` — `#3d3d56`): Paragraph text. Softer than ink but never gray — maintains readability for listing details.
- **Muted** (`{colors.muted}` — `#6b6b80`): Secondary info — area descriptions, rating counts, footer text. Readable but recessed.
- **Muted Soft** (`{colors.muted-soft}` — `#9999aa`): Placeholder and disabled text.

### Borders & Structure
- **Hairline** (`{colors.hairline}` — `#e8e8e4`): Warm-tinted 1px dividers. Slightly warm to match the canvas.
- **Hairline Strong** (`{colors.hairline-strong}` — `#d0d0cc`): Stronger borders and ad banner dashes.
- **Border Card** (`{colors.border-card}` — `#e2e2de`): Card border color when shadow isn't enough.

### Semantic & Functional
- **Star** (`{colors.star}` — `#f59e0b`): Gold for star ratings — universal trust signal for business listings.
- **Link** (`{colors.link}` — `#1a5276`): Interactive text links — lighter than primary for inline use, darker on hover.
- **Success / Warning / Error**: Standard semantic colors for form states and notifications.

### Gradient
The hero and CTA sections use a three-stop gradient (`{colors.gradient-hero-start}` → `{colors.gradient-hero-mid}` → `{colors.gradient-hero-end}`). This gradient is the only decorative element on the page — it creates depth and visual interest in the header/footer bands without requiring photography.

## Typography

### Font Family
**Inter** for everything. It's free, it's excellent at directory-relevant sizes (14-22px), and it has a full weight range. The system stack (`-apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, 'Segoe UI', Roboto, sans-serif`) is the fallback.

No monospace face is needed for this site — directory listings don't require it. If technical content is added later, consider adding JetBrains Mono as a `code` token.

### Hierarchy

| Token | Size | Weight | Line Height | Tracking | Use |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| `{typography.display-xl}` | 2.2rem (35px) | 700 | 1.2 | -0.02em | Hero title ("North NJ Services") |
| `{typography.display-md}` | 1.5rem (24px) | 600 | 1.3 | -0.01em | Category card headings, CTA headings |
| `{typography.display-sm}` | 1.25rem (20px) | 600 | 1.35 | 0 | Business name in listing cards |
| `{typography.heading-section}` | 1.5rem (24px) | 600 | 1.3 | -0.01em | Section titles ("Browse by Category") |
| `{typography.body-lg}` | 1.1rem (18px) | 400 | 1.6 | 0 | Hero subtitle, CTA body text |
| `{typography.body-md}` | 1rem (16px) | 400 | 1.6 | 0 | Default body, category descriptions |
| `{typography.body-sm}` | 0.9rem (14px) | 400 | 1.5 | 0 | Business details, card descriptions |
| `{typography.caption}` | 0.8rem (13px) | 400 | 1.4 | 0 | Area text, rating counts, fine print |
| `{typography.label-caps}` | 0.75rem (12px) | 600 | 1.4 | 0.05em | Category labels, count badges, "COMING SOON" |
| `{typography.button-md}` | 0.9rem (14px) | 600 | 1.4 | 0 | Nav links, secondary buttons |
| `{typography.button-lg}` | 1rem (16px) | 600 | 1.4 | 0 | Primary CTAs ("Get in Touch", "Submit Listing") |

### Principles
- **Mobile readability is king.** Body text never goes below 14px. The smallest functional text is 12px for labels only.
- **Weight contrast creates hierarchy.** Headings at 600-700, body at 400. Never use 300 or below.
- **No uppercase headings.** Category names and headings are sentence case. The only uppercase is in `{typography.label-caps}` for metadata badges.
- **Warm tracking.** Section headings get slight negative tracking (-0.01em to -0.02em) for visual tightness. Body stays at default.
- **Emoji are functional icons.** Each category has exactly one emoji that serves as an icon — no emoji in headings or body text.

## Layout

### Spacing System
- **Base unit**: 4px (all spacing values are multiples of 4)
- **Section padding**: 80px (`{spacing.section}`) top/bottom for major sections, 48px (`{spacing.2xl}`) for compact sections
- **Card interior**: 24px (`{spacing.lg}`) padding on all sides — generous for readability
- **Card grid gap**: 16px (`{spacing.md}`) on mobile, 24px (`{spacing.lg}`) on desktop
- **Container max-width**: 1200px centered with 16px gutters on mobile, 24px on desktop

### Grid & Container
- **Max width**: 1200px — narrower than tech sites because directory content benefits from tighter, more scannable columns
- **Category grid**: `repeat(auto-fill, minmax(280px, 1fr))` — responsive 2-4 columns
- **Business listing grid**: `repeat(auto-fill, minmax(340px, 1fr))` — responsive 1-3 columns with more room for addresses and phone numbers
- **Nav**: Horizontal sticky bar, flex-wrap on mobile

### Whitespace Philosophy
The directory is a scanning experience. Cards need breathing room between them, and text inside cards needs generous line-height (1.5-1.6). The warm canvas background fills the gaps — it's never "wasted space," it's reading room. The 3px left border on business cards creates a visual rhythm that helps the eye track down a list without requiring heavy dividers.

### Responsive Strategy

| Breakpoint | Width | Layout Changes |
|---|---|---|
| Mobile | < 600px | Single column, full-width cards, stacked hero |
| Tablet | 600-959px | 2-column grids, nav wraps |
| Desktop | ≥ 960px | 3-4 column category grid, 2-3 column listing grid |

On mobile:
- Hero text scales down (2.2rem → 1.6rem)
- Cards go single column, full width
- Nav collapses to horizontal scroll if needed
- CTA sections stack vertically
- Business card left border increases to 4px for visibility

## Elevation & Depth

| Level | Treatment | Use |
|---|---|---|
| Level 0 — Flat | No shadow, no border | Hero background, footer, CTA bands |
| Level 1 — Card | `0 2px 8px rgba(0,0,0,0.07)` | Default category and business cards |
| Level 2 — Hover | `0 4px 16px rgba(0,0,0,0.12) + translateY(-2px)` | Card hover state |
| Level 3 — Sticky Nav | No shadow, solid dark background | Sticky navigation bar |

### Shadow Philosophy
Keep it subtle. Directory users are scanning — they don't need dramatic floating cards. Level 1 shadows are barely visible, just enough to separate cards from the warm canvas. The left-border accent on business cards does more visual work than the shadow. Hover elevation is gentle — `translateY(-2px)` with a slightly deeper shadow, not a dramatic lift.

## Shapes

| Token | Value | Use |
|---|---|---|
| `{rounded.none}` | 0px | CTA buttons — sharp corners feel direct and trustworthy |
| `{rounded.xs}` | 4px | Nav links, small interactive elements |
| `{rounded.sm}` | 6px | Form inputs |
| `{rounded.md}` | 8px | Cards — the primary shape for all listing and category cards |
| `{rounded.lg}` | 12px | CTA section containers |
| `{rounded.xl}` | 16px | Hero and feature cards (future) |
| `{rounded.pill}` | 9999px | Count badges, coming-soon labels, rating pills |

### Shape Philosophy
Cards are softly rounded (8px) — friendly without being bubbly. CTAs use sharp corners (4px or less) — direct and trustworthy, matching the "call to action" urgency. Badges and labels are full pills — they float above the content as metadata.

## Components

### Navigation (`nav-bar`)
Sticky dark navbar with warm white text. Horizontal link row with hover highlights. Logo left, category links center, CTA right. On mobile, links wrap naturally. The dark background creates clear visual separation from the warm canvas content below.

### Hero Banner (`hero-banner`)
Full-width gradient band using the three-stop navy gradient. Contains site title (`display-xl`), tagline (`body-lg`), and optional CTA button (`hero-cta`). Padding is generous — the hero should feel like a welcoming header, not a cramped banner.

### Section Title (`section-title`)
Left-aligned heading with coral underline (`2px solid {colors.accent}`). Creates a visual break between sections and anchors the eye when scrolling.

### Category Card (`cat-card`)
The primary browsing unit. White card on warm canvas, 8px radius, 24px padding, subtle shadow. Contains emoji icon, heading (navy), description (body gray), and coral count badge. On hover: gentle lift (`translateY(-2px)`) and deeper shadow. Each card links to its category page.

### Business Listing Card (`biz-card`)
The primary information unit. White card with 3px left navy border, 8px radius, 24px padding. Contains: business name (`display-sm`), category label (`label-caps` in coral), details (address, phone, hours in `body-sm`), area served (`caption` in muted), optional star rating, and website link. The left border creates a visual rhythm in list view.

### CTA Section (`cta-section`)
Full-width coral gradient band with white text and white button. Used for "Need Tech Help?" and "List Your Business" prompts. The gradient (coral → deeper coral) adds warmth without requiring images.

### Ad Banner (`ad-banner`)
Dashed-border, soft-gray placeholder for future advertising. Honest and unobtrusive — clearly labeled "Advertisement" so it doesn't confuse with organic content.

### Footer (`footer`)
Dark navy band matching the header. Contains copyright, links (`footer-link` in coral), and minimal text in muted gray. Symmetrical with the header creates a visual frame.

### Coming Soon Badge (`coming-soon-badge`)
Soft pill badge for categories not yet populated. Muted gray on soft background — honest signaling that content is planned, not fake listings.

## Do's and Don'ts

### Do
- Use `{colors.accent}` coral sparingly — for CTAs, count badges, and category labels. It should pop, not blanket the page.
- Keep card interiors spacious — 24px padding minimum. Business names and phone numbers need room to breathe.
- Use the left-border accent (`3px solid {colors.primary}`) on business cards to create scan-friendly rhythm.
- Make star ratings prominent — they're a trust signal that helps users choose quickly.
- Use emoji category icons consistently — one emoji per category, placed at the top of each card.
- Use `{colors.canvas-warm}` (`#f8f7f4`) as the page background, never pure white. The warmth is part of the brand.
- Keep the sticky nav — directory users switch categories frequently while browsing.
- Show listing counts honestly — if a category has 3 listings, show "3 listings", not "3+"
- Use `{colors.muted}` for secondary info like area served and rating counts — it should be readable but recessive.

### Don't
- Don't use the navy gradient outside of hero/CTA bands — it's too heavy for cards or inline elements.
- Don't add decorative shadows beyond Level 1-2. Directory cards should feel grounded, not floating.
- Don't use emoji in headings or body text — they're category icons only.
- Don't mix serif and sans-serif. Inter only. If you need variety, use weight (400/600/700) not face changes.
- Don't use `{colors.accent}` as a background fill for large areas — it's an action color, not a surface color.
- Don't hide "Coming Soon" categories — show them with muted badges so users know what's planned.
- Don't use pure black (`#000`) for any text — use `{colors.ink}` (`#1a1a2e`) which has enough blue to feel cohesive.
- Don't use rounded corners on CTA buttons sharper than `{rounded.xs}` (4px) — the sharpness signals action, while cards stay soft.
- Don't exceed 3 lines for category descriptions on cards — if it's longer, edit the copy, don't expand the card.